T1  - Optimal Taxation and Strategic Budget Deficit Under Political Regime Switching
PY  - 2001
Y1  - 2001/07/01
DO  - 10.1111/1467-937X.00181
JO  - The Review of Economic Studies
JA  - Rev Econ Stud
VL  - 68
IS  - 3
SP  - 573
EP  - 592
SN  - 0034-6527
AB  - I develop a dynamic political economy theory of optimal taxation and budget distortions in a model with partisan politics. Under asymmetric information, politics affects the distribution of utilities in the economy. Political regime switching introduces fluctuations of this distribution. These fluctuations justify strategic budget distortions by governments currently holding office and willing to favour their redistributive concerns against future majority. Under quite general assumptions on preferences, these distortions take the form of budget deficits (resp. surpluses) with leftist (rightist) governments. Endogenizing the probabilities of getting elected may reverse this result.
Y2  - 3/25/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/1467-937X.00181
ER  - 



